# config/sudoers.d/sovereign-os-cockpit — DRAFT / PREVIEW (SUPERSEDED-BY design)
# ============================================================================
# ⚠ This is the PREVIEW of the controls-bucket NOPASSWD allowlist that lets the
# cockpit panels EXECUTE sovereign-os-owned control verbs (realizing R10274; the
# manual `sovereign-osctl …` command stays the fallback).
#
# CANONICAL HOME (per SDD-047 Q-047-A/C, answered from evidence 2026-07-08):
# this content BELONGS as an added bucket in the existing generator
# `scripts/operator/operator-sudoers.sh` (on `main`), NOT a hand-authored file.
# That generator already grants the OPERATOR USER — the user the panel APIs +
# the AI agent run as — a scoped `Cmnd_Alias SOVEREIGN_OS_OPS` (diagnostics +
# image-inspection). The functional-execution work adds a SECOND scoped alias
# (`SOVEREIGN_OS_COCKPIT`, below) for the 9 sovereign-os-OWNED control verbs.
# On branch-recreate-from-main this file is replaced by extending that script;
# `_action_exec.py` then runs `sudo -n sovereign-osctl <verb>` as the operator
# user (no dedicated user, no `NoNewPrivileges` change — Q-047-C).
#
# INSTALL TARGET (once folded in): /etc/sudoers.d/sovereign-os-operator (0440)
# Validate:  visudo -cf config/sudoers.d/sovereign-os-cockpit
#
# Two-gate defence (unchanged): `_action_exec.py` validates every placeholder
# against the control's `options` allowlist / a strict no-metacharacter regex
# BEFORE sudo; this allowlist is the second gate. selfdef + perimeter are
# DELIBERATELY ABSENT — selfdef-owned, they stay a signed proxy (R10212).
# The operator user is resolved by operator-sudoers.sh (SUDO_USER / repo owner /
# SOVEREIGN_OS_OPERATOR_USER); the literal below is a placeholder for preview.
# ============================================================================

